\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
To show how income and substitution effects can lead to our results, we
 write down a simple model of fertility choices.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is an individual's wage.
 Raising a child takes time 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 People maximize utility composed of two subcomponents, earnings and the
 number of children 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 An individual's payoff is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(N)=u(\bar{W})+aN
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{W}\equiv(1-bN)W$
\end_inset

 is earnings from time not allocated to childcare, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 captures the strength of preference for children.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is concave and increasing.
 We treat 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 as continuous, in line with the literature: this can be thought of as the
 expected number of children among people who share the same characteristics.
 The marginal benefit of an extra child is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dU}{dN}=-bWu'(\bar{W})+a
\]

\end_inset

and the effect of an increase in wages on this marginal benefit is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}U}{dNdW}=\underbrace{-bu'(\bar{W})}_{\textrm{Substitution effect}}\underbrace{-b\bar{W}u''(\bar{W})}_{\textrm{Income effect}}.
\]

\end_inset

The first term is negative and reflects that when 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 increases, time devoted to childcare costs more.
 The second term is positive, and reflects that when 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is higher, the marginal loss of wages from childcare has less effect on
 overall utility â€“ as captured by the concavity of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the model explicitly, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 be the 
\emph on
constant relative risk aversion
\emph default
 function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(w)=\frac{w^{1-\sigma}-1}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>0$
\end_inset

 parametrizes the level of risk aversion in wages, and 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(w)=w^{-\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
 Differentiating and setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dU}{dN}=0$
\end_inset

 gives the first order condition for an optimal choice of children 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{*}>0$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{bW}{(W(1-bN^{*}))^{\sigma}}=a.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Q\equiv\left(\frac{b}{a}W\right)^{1/\sigma} & =(W-bNW)\\
N^{*} & =\frac{W-Q}{bW}\\
 & =\frac{1}{b}-\frac{Q}{bW}\\
 & =\frac{1}{b}-\frac{b^{(1-\sigma)/\sigma}}{a^{1/\sigma}}W^{(1-\sigma)/\sigma}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Rearranging gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N^{*}=\max\left\{ \frac{1}{b}\left(1-\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)^{1/\sigma}W^{(1-\sigma)/\sigma}\right),0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Differentiating gives the effect of wages on fertility for 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{*}>0$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dN^{*}}{dW}=-\frac{1}{b}\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)^{1/\sigma}\frac{1-\sigma}{\sigma}W^{(1-2\sigma)/\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

which is signed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma-1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, when risk aversion is low (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<1$
\end_inset

), fertility decreases in wages.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}N^{*}}{dW^{2}}\textrm{ is signed by }(\sigma-1)(1-2\sigma)
\]

\end_inset

where the second term comes from the exponent on 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $1>\sigma>1/2$
\end_inset

, this is positive, so the effect of fertility on wages shrinks towards
 zero as wages increase.
 Lastly, we consider the time cost of children 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dN^{*}}{dW} & =-\frac{1}{b}\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)^{1/\sigma}\frac{1-\sigma}{\sigma}W^{(1-2\sigma)/\sigma}\\
 & =-b^{(1-\sigma)/\sigma}\left(\frac{1}{a}\right)^{1/\sigma}\frac{1-\sigma}{\sigma}W^{(1-2\sigma)/\sigma}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}N^{*}}{dbdW}=-\left(\frac{1}{a}\right)^{1/\sigma}\left(\frac{1-\sigma}{\sigma}\right)^{2}W^{(1-2\sigma)/\sigma}b^{(1-2\sigma)/\sigma}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}N^{*}}{dWdb}=-\left(\frac{1}{a}\right)^{1/\sigma}\left(\frac{1-\sigma}{\sigma}\right)^{2}(Wb)^{(1-2\sigma)/\sigma}<0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is higher for single parents than for couples, then the effect of wages
 on fertility will be more negative for single parents.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To sum up, in this model, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<1$
\end_inset

, fertility decreases in market wage 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 Wages are known to be affected by human capital, including genetic components
 of human capital.
 Polygenic scores which cause, or even correlate with, variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 would then show the pattern we observe in our data: a negative correlation
 with fertility at low income levels, and a smaller or zero correlation
 at high income levels.
 Also, the fertility decrease is steeper when the time burden of children
 is larger, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5<\sigma<1$
\end_inset

, the fertility decrease is steeper at lower wages.
 These predictions fit the patterns in our data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This model is a simple illustration of how the interaction between fertility
 and wages can explain the patterns we observe.
 In the appendix, we extend it to examine birth timing, education, and marriage.
 We also discuss other models of fertility from the economic literature,
 as well as causal evidence for the relationship between earnings and fertility.
\end_layout

