\begin_layout Standard
We next consider the effect of education.
 Instead of identifying human capital with wages, we treat it and education
 as complementary inputs to productivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there are two periods.
 For convenience we ignore time discounting and assume the interest rate
 is 0; we also assume that there are no credit markets.
 Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(N_{1},N_{2})=u(\bar{W}_{1})+u(\bar{W}_{2})+a(N_{1}+N_{2})
\]

\end_inset

We continue to assume CRRA utility.
 We now normalize period 1 wages to 1, and allow individuals to choose a
 level of education 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, which has a cost in time in period 1.
 Education increases period 2 wages, and is complementary to an individual's
 human capital 
\begin_inset Formula $h>0$
\end_inset

, so that the net wage in period 2 is 
\begin_inset Formula $w(e,h)$
\end_inset

.
 We assume the simple functional form 
\begin_inset Formula $w(e,h)=eh$
\end_inset

.
 Thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{W}_{1} & =1-e-bN_{1}\\
\bar{W}_{2} & =w(e,h)(1-bN_{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

